---
import UswdsLayout from "../layouts/UswdsLayout.astro";
---

<UswdsLayout
  title="Documentation | Ride Conditions"
  description="Read project documentation for Ride Conditions."
>
  <section class="usa-section app-intro">
    <div class="grid-container">
      <div class="grid-row grid-gap">
        <div class="tablet:grid-col-8">
          <p class="usa-intro">Documentation</p>
          <h1>Ride journal usage guidelines.</h1>
          <p>
            Use this guidance to decide when the ride journal pattern fits a
            workflow, what content it should ask for, and how to keep the
            experience usable, accessible, and implementation-ready.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="usa-section" aria-labelledby="pattern-fit-heading">
    <div class="grid-container">
      <div class="grid-row grid-gap">
        <aside class="tablet:grid-col-4 desktop:grid-col-3">
          <nav aria-label="Ride journal guidance">
            <ul class="usa-sidenav">
              <li class="usa-sidenav__item">
                <a href="#when-to-use">When to use</a>
              </li>
              <li class="usa-sidenav__item">
                <a href="#when-not-to-use">When not to use</a>
              </li>
              <li class="usa-sidenav__item">
                <a href="#content-guidance">Content guidance</a>
              </li>
              <li class="usa-sidenav__item">
                <a href="#validation-guidance">Validation guidance</a>
              </li>
              <li class="usa-sidenav__item">
                <a href="#accessibility-notes">Accessibility notes</a>
              </li>
              <li class="usa-sidenav__item">
                <a href="#implementation-notes">Implementation notes</a>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </nav>
        </aside>

        <div class="tablet:grid-col-8 desktop:grid-col-7">
          <h2 id="pattern-fit-heading">Pattern fit</h2>
          <p>
            The ride journal pattern is a structured form-and-review flow for
            recording a ride after it happens or while the details are still
            fresh. It combines rider-entered details with normalized address and
            public weather context so saved entries can be compared later.
          </p>

          <h3 id="when-to-use">When to use</h3>
          <ul class="usa-list">
            <li>
              Use it when riders need to save a durable record of a completed or
              planned ride, including date, location, mileage, duration, effort,
              and notes.
            </li>
            <li>
              Use it when the location can be resolved to coordinates and paired
              with public conditions such as forecast summary, temperature, and
              wind.
            </li>
            <li>
              Use it when the workflow benefits from a confirmation step before
              saving normalized or enriched details.
            </li>
            <li>
              Use it when entries need to appear later in a saved-rides list,
              history view, export, or portfolio demonstration.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 id="when-not-to-use">When not to use</h3>
          <ul class="usa-list">
            <li>
              Do not use it for live turn-by-turn navigation, emergency
              reporting, or safety-critical ride decisions.
            </li>
            <li>
              Do not use it when a single lightweight note or checklist would be
              enough and weather or location enrichment would add unnecessary
              friction.
            </li>
            <li>
              Do not require it when riders need to browse general route ideas,
              compare maps, or inspect saved rides without creating a new entry.
            </li>
            <li>
              Do not collect precise private location details unless the product
              has appropriate user authentication, retention rules, and privacy
              language in place.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="content-guidance">Content guidance</h2>
          <p>
            Ask for only the details needed to make a ride entry useful later.
            Keep required fields focused on facts that support comparison and
            retrieval. Keep subjective reflections optional.
          </p>
          <ul class="usa-list">
            <li>
              Group date and starting location under a clear "When and where"
              legend.
            </li>
            <li>
              Use plain labels such as "Distance in miles" and "Duration in
              minutes" instead of abbreviations.
            </li>
            <li>
              Offer a small effort scale with familiar words: easy, moderate,
              and hard.
            </li>
            <li>
              Separate weather notes from ride notes so rider observations do
              not get mixed with route memories.
            </li>
            <li>
              Show weather data as supporting context, not as a replacement for
              rider judgment or field observations.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="validation-guidance">Validation guidance</h2>
          <p>
            Validate early enough to prevent unusable entries, but do not block
            the rider because a third-party lookup is temporarily unavailable.
          </p>
          <ul class="usa-list">
            <li>
              Mark required fields visibly and connect each required control to
              native HTML validation with <code>required</code>,
              <code>min</code>, <code>step</code>, <code>pattern</code>, or the
              relevant input type.
            </li>
            <li>
              Place a validation summary before the form groups and move focus
              to it when submission fails.
            </li>
            <li>
              Link each validation-summary item to the field that needs
              attention.
            </li>
            <li>
              Treat address and weather lookup failures as recoverable states:
              explain the issue, preserve entered values, and allow the rider to
              edit or continue where appropriate.
            </li>
            <li>
              Normalize data in the review step so riders can confirm the
              address label, weather summary, and activity values before saving.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="accessibility-notes">Accessibility notes</h2>
          <ul class="usa-list">
            <li>
              Use semantic <code>fieldset</code> and <code>legend</code>
              elements for each related field group.
            </li>
            <li>
              Keep status messages in polite live regions for background address
              and weather lookups.
            </li>
            <li>
              Use <code>role="alert"</code> for blocking validation errors and
              save failures that need immediate attention.
            </li>
            <li>
              Give form headings <code>tabindex="-1"</code> when scripts move
              focus to a new step such as review mode.
            </li>
            <li>
              Ensure labels, hints, and error text are programmatically tied to
              their controls.
            </li>
            <li>
              Preserve keyboard order from form entry to review, edit, and save.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="implementation-notes">Implementation notes</h2>
          <p>
            Build the pattern as a progressive form first, then enhance it with
            address lookup, weather lookup, review, and persistence. The current
            implementation lives in <code>src/pages/journal.astro</code> and
            uses Amplify client calls from <code>src/lib/amplifyClient.ts</code>.
          </p>
          <pre><code class="language-html">&lt;form class="usa-form usa-form--large" novalidate data-journal-form&gt;
  &lt;div class="usa-alert usa-alert--error" role="alert" tabindex="-1" hidden&gt;
    &lt;div class="usa-alert__body"&gt;
      &lt;h2 class="usa-alert__heading"&gt;Correct the highlighted fields.&lt;/h2&gt;
      &lt;ul class="usa-list" id="journal-validation-list"&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;

  &lt;fieldset class="usa-fieldset"&gt;
    &lt;legend class="usa-legend usa-legend--large"&gt;When and where&lt;/legend&gt;
    &lt;label class="usa-label" for="ride-date"&gt;Ride date&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input class="usa-input" id="ride-date" name="ride-date" type="date" required /&gt;
  &lt;/fieldset&gt;

  &lt;button class="usa-button" type="submit"&gt;Continue&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>
          <ul class="usa-list">
            <li>
              Keep weather and geocoding values in hidden inputs only after the
              rider-provided address has been resolved.
            </li>
            <li>
              Do not save generated lookup data without also saving the
              human-readable source or status shown to the rider.
            </li>
            <li>
              Keep generated sandbox outputs and local credentials out of git.
            </li>
            <li>
              Before release, test the form with keyboard navigation, browser
              zoom, screen-reader announcements, failed lookups, and failed save
              states.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</UswdsLayout>
